Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Part 1 - Defining the Variables", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985091030280538*^9, 3.985091125689316*^9}, {
  3.9850911798462257`*^9, 3.985091208687347*^9}, {3.985091246828575*^9, 
  3.985091281776403*^9}, {3.9850967682822123`*^9, 
  3.98509677545953*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e6d63926-5f1e-4520-9346-\
d9fb04812268"],

Cell["\<\
First, we start off the defining the gravitational constant, G, the masses of \
the star, planet, and moon, and their respective distance from their orbital \
parents (That is, the distance of the planet from the star and the distance \
from the planet to the moon). We\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll use SI units for now but \
also set G=100 for simplicity. Later on, however, we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll use \
a more realistic gravitational constant. The masses of the star, planet, and \
moon, respectively, are m1, m2, and m3 and their respective orbital distances \
from their orbital parents are r1, r2, and r3 (the star\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
orbital distance is 0 because it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s the most massive body in \
the system). We will also set these with controls so we can observe later how \
changing these parameters affects the orbits.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.985096762345228*^9, {3.985200351764724*^9, 3.9852003564304333`*^9}, {
   3.985448259564164*^9, 3.98544825971412*^9}, {3.9855376828366213`*^9, 
   3.98553769812328*^9}, {3.985537730573138*^9, 
   3.9855377660687943`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8958cceb-b112-4462-a5de-\
ef394789f4a8"],

